	<p>For large positive values of <m>x</m> and for large negative values of <m>x</m>, the <m>x^2</m> term dominates, which is why its coefficient will determine whether the parabola points up or down.</p>


        <exercise>
            <introduction>
                <p>Determine if the graph of each quadratic function points up or down.</p>
            </introduction>
            <webwork >
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        Context()->variables->are();
                        for my $i (1..26) {
                            Context()->variables->add($ALPHABET[$i-1]=>'Real');
                            Context()->variables->add(lc($ALPHABET[$i-1])=>'Real');
                            };
                        Context()->strings->add('up'=>{});
                        Context()->strings->add('down'=>{});
                   </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p><ol label="a">
                        <li>
                            <p>The graph of the quadratic function <m>y=3x^2-4x-7</m> points <var name="up" width="6"/>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>The graph of the quadratic function <m>y=-5x^2+x</m> points <var name="down" width="6"/>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>The graph of the quadratic function <m>y=2+3x-x^2</m> points <var name="down" width="6"/>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>The graph of the quadratic function <m>y=\frac{1}{3}x^2-\frac{2}{5}x+\frac{1}{4}</m> points <var name="up" width="6"/>.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><ol label="a">
                        <li>
                            <p>The graph of the quadratic function <m>y=3x^2-4x-7</m> points up as the leading coefficient is the positive number <m>3</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>The graph of the quadratic function <m>y=-5x^2+x</m> points down as the leading coefficient is the negative number <m>-5</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>The graph of the quadratic function <m>y=2+3x-x^2</m> points down as the leading coefficient is <m>-1</m>. (Note that the leading coefficient is the coefficient on <m>x^2</m>.)</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>The graph of the quadratic function <m>y=\frac{1}{3}x^2-\frac{2}{5}x+\frac{1}{4}</m> points up as the leading coefficient is the positive number <m>\frac{1}{3}</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol></p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>


