	<subsection>
		<title>Algebraically Determining Horizontal and Vertical Intercepts</title>

        <p>In <xref ref="list-properties-of-quadratic-functions-visual">List</xref>, we identified that horizontal intercepts occur where the graph of a function intersects the horizontal axis and that the vertical intercept occurs where the graph of a function intersects the vertical axis. If we're using <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> as our variables, this means that the <m>x</m>-intercept(s) occur where <m>y=0</m>, and the <m>y</m>-intercept occurs where <m>x=0</m>. These might seem the reverse of what you'd expect, but it's important to remember that when finding the <m>\highlight{{}x{}}</m>-intercept, we want to determine the value(s) of <m>\highlight{{}x{}}</m> when <m>y</m> is set to zero. Similarly, when determining the <m>\highlight{{}y{}}</m>-intercept, we want to determine the value of <m>\highlight{{}y{}}</m> when <m>x</m> is zero. We'll now look at determining these algebraically when given the formula of a quadratic function.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-introduction-to-algebraically-determining-intercepts">
            <p>Algebraically determine the <m>x</m>-intercept(s) and <m>y</m>-intercept for the quadratic function <m>y=x^2-4x-12</m>.</p>

            <p>To determine the <m>x</m>-intercept(s), we will set <m>y</m> to zero and solve for <m>x</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=x^2-4x-12</mrow>
                    <mrow>\substitute{0}\amp=x^2-4x-12</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp=(x-6)(x+2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp-6=0,\ x+2=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=6,\ x=-2</mrow>
                </md>
                So the <m>x</m>-intercepts occur where <m>x=6</m> and where <m>x=-2</m>. On a graph, these associate with the points <m>(6,0)</m> and <m>(-2,0)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>To determine the <m>y</m>-intercept, we will set <m>x</m> to zero and solve for <m>x</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=x^2-4x-12</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=\substitute{0}^2-4(\substitute{0})-12</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-12</mrow>
                </md>
                So the <m>y</m>-intercept occurs where <m>y=-12</m>. On a graph, this associates with the points <m>(0,-12)</m>.
            </p>
        </example>


	</subsection>
	<subsection>
		<title>Algebraically Determining the Vertex</title>

		<p>The vertex of a quadratic function is either the minimum point or the maximum point on its graph, depending on whether this function points up or down. When there are two horizontal intercepts for a quadratic function, we can see that the vertex occurs half-way between those two points. Similarly, when there is exactly one horizontal intercept, we know that this point is where the vertex occurs.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
				<figure xml:id="figure-quadratic-function-two-horizontal-intercepts">
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=x^2+x-6</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-4.14:3.14] {(x-2)*(x+3)};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,0)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,0)} ;
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

				<figure xml:id="figure-quadratic-one-horizontal-intercept">
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=-(x-1)^2</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-4.646:0.646] {-1*(x+2)^2};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,0)} ;
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

		<p>This visual method is quick, but it can only be used in limited cases.</p>

		<fact><p>The vertex of a quadratic function <m>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m> occurs where <m>x=-\frac{b}{2a}</m>, or at the point <m>\left(-\frac{b}{2a},f\left(-\frac{b}{2a}\right)\right)</m>.</p></fact>

		<p>This formula at first seems a bit random, but is actually related to the quadratic formula. Still thinking about the vertex occuring in the middle of two horizontal intercepts, we can see that this value is in the middle of the two values obtained from the quadratic formula:
			<me>x=\frac{{}\highlight{-b}{}\pm \lowlight{\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}}{{}\highlight{2a}{}}</me>
		</p>

		<example>
            <p>Algebraically determine the vertex of the quadratic function <m>y=x^2-4x-12</m>.</p>

            <p>To algebraically determine this vertex, we could rely on the horizontal intercepts determined in <xref ref="example-introduction-to-algebraically-determining-intercepts">Example</xref>. To do so, we'll note that the vertex and axis of symmetry will occur halfway between <m>x=6</m> and <m>x=-2</m>, which is at <m>x=2</m>. Visually, this looks like:</p>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,0) (6,0)} ;
                                \addplot[guideline]coordinates {(2,-7) (2,7)} node[pin=220:{axis of symmetry}]{};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
        <p>We could also determine the <m>x</m>-value where the vertex occurs using the formula <m>x=-\frac{b}{2a}</m>. Noting that for <m>y=x^2-4x-12</m> we have <m>a=1</m> and <m>b=-4</m>, we have:
            <md>
                <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{-4}{2(1)}</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=2</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>Now that we've determined that the <m>x</m>-value where the vertex occurs is <m>2</m>, we will replace <m>x</m> with <m>2</m> in the original equation to determine <m>y</m>:
            <md>
                <mrow>y\amp=x^2-4x-12</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=(\substitute{2})^2-4(\substitute{2})-12</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=4-8-12</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=-16</mrow>
            </md>
        The vertex is therefore the point <m>(2,-16)</m>.
        </p>

        </example>
	</subsection>

